revision.text:
'''Orochon Fire Festival''' (オロチョンの火祭り) is a {{ill|festival|ja|祭り|12=draft|12=draft}} held as part of the events in {{ill|Abashiri, Hokkaido|ja|網走市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道|12=draft|12=draft}}.
The festival is a ritual performed to honor the spirits of indigenous peoples and pray for abundance. Participants dress in traditional clothing of northern minority groups and dance around flames to the accompaniment of {{ill|drums|ja|太鼓|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|khomus|ja|コロホル|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== History == Abashiri, located along the {{ill|Sea of Okhotsk|ja|オホーツク海|12=draft|12=draft}}, has historically had active exchanges with northern peoples. At the {{ill|Moyoro Shell Mound|ja|モヨロ貝塚|12=draft|12=draft}}, human remains of the {{ill|Okhotsk people|ja|オホーツク人|12=draft|12=draft}}, some of whom became ancestors of the {{ill|Ainu|ja|アイヌ民族|12=draft|12=draft}}, have been discovered. In light of these historical connections, a festival called "Moyoro Festival" was held at the Moyoro Shell Mound around {{ill|1940|ja|1940th year|12=draft|12=draft}} to honor the spirits of northern peoples.
In {{ill|1950|ja|1950th year|12=draft|12=draft}}, after World War II, the festival evolved into the "Orochon Fire Festival," with cooperation from {{ill|Oroks|ja|ウィルタ|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Nivkh|ja|ニヴフ|12=draft|12=draft}} peoples who had repatriated from {{ill|Karafuto|ja|樺太|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was incorporated as an official summer festival of the city. Later, it became part of the "Comeback Salmon in Lake Abashiri" event held annually from {{ill|October 1|ja|10月1日|12=draft|12=draft}}, gaining popularity as a tourism attraction.
== About the Name == The term "{{ill|Oroqen_people|lt=Orochon|ja|オロチョン族|12=draft|12=draft}}" originally refers to a {{ill|Tungusic peoples|ja|ツングース|12=draft|12=draft}} group residing within {{ill|Russia|ja|ロシア|12=draft|12=draft}}. However, in {{ill|Japan|ja|日本|12=draft|12=draft}}, the term was used more broadly to denote "northern peoples" during a certain period. This legacy led to the naming of the festival as the Orochon Fire Festival. Notably, no ritual resembling a "fire festival" exists in the culture of the Orochon people as they are known today. == See Also == * {{ill|Oroqen_people|lt=Orochon people|ja|オロチョン族|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Lake Abashiri|ja|網走湖|12=draft|12=draft}}
