The festival is a ritual performed to honor the spirits of indigenous peoples and pray for abundance. Participants dress in traditional clothing of northern minority groups and dance around flames to the accompaniment of {{ill|drums|ja|太鼓|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/drums|qq=}} and {{ill|khomus|ja|コロホル|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/khomus|qq=}}.
== History == Abashiri, located along the {{ill|Sea of Okhotsk|ja|オホーツク海|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sea of Okhotsk|qq=}}, has historically had active exchanges with northern peoples. At the {{ill|Moyoro Shell Mound|ja|モヨロ貝塚|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moyoro Shell Mound|qq=}}, human remains of the {{ill|Okhotsk people|ja|オホーツク人|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okhotsk people|qq=}}, some of whom became ancestors of the {{ill|Ainu|ja|アイヌ民族|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ainu|qq=}}, have been discovered. In light of these historical connections, a festival called "Moyoro Festival" was held at the Moyoro Shell Mound around {{ill|1940|ja|1940th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1940|qq=}} to honor the spirits of northern peoples.
In {{ill|1950|ja|1950th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1950|qq=}}, after World War II, the festival evolved into the "Orochon Fire Festival," with cooperation from {{ill|Oroks|ja|ウィルタ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oroks|qq=}} and {{ill|Nivkh|ja|ニヴフ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nivkh|qq=}} peoples who had repatriated from {{ill|Karafuto|ja|樺太|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Karafuto|qq=}}. It was incorporated as an official summer festival of the city. Later, it became part of the "Comeback Salmon in Lake Abashiri" event held annually from {{ill|October 1|ja|10月1日|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/October 1|qq=}}, gaining popularity as a tourism attraction.
== About the Name == The term "{{ill|Oroqen_people|lt=Orochon|ja|オロチョン族|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oroqen_people|qq=}}" originally refers to a {{ill|Tungusic peoples|ja|ツングース|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tungusic peoples|qq=}} group residing within {{ill|Russia|ja|ロシア|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Russia|qq=}}. However, in {{ill|Japan|ja|日本|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japan|qq=}}, the term was used more broadly to denote "northern peoples" during a certain period. This legacy led to the naming of the festival as the Orochon Fire Festival. Notably, no ritual resembling a "fire festival" exists in the culture of the Orochon people as they are known today. == See Also == * {{ill|Oroqen_people|lt=Orochon people|ja|オロチョン族|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oroqen_people|qq=}} * {{ill|Lake Abashiri|ja|網走湖|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lake Abashiri|qq=}}
